  <div class="article-content">
    <section id="introduction" class="reveal">
  <p>Two-thirds. That is the number that has haunted every clinical conversation about stopping semaglutide since 2022 — the fraction of lost weight that STEP-1 trial participants regained within a single year of discontinuation. It shaped how physicians counsel patients. It shaped how insurers justify coverage requirements. It shaped the quiet dread that settles over anyone who has lost 40 pounds on Ozempic and is now staring down a gap in their prescription coverage. Two-thirds back. Within twelve months. The data were unambiguous.</p>
  <p>Then, on March 12, 2026, a team led by Hamlet Gasoyan, PhD, at the Cleveland Clinic published a retrospective cohort study in <em>Diabetes, Obesity and Metabolism</em>. The sample: 7,938 adults who had stopped semaglutide or tirzepatide in real-world clinical practice. The average weight regain among obesity patients one year after stopping: 0.5%. Not 50%. Not two-thirds. Half a percentage point.</p>
  <p>Sit in that gap for a moment. Don't explain it yet. Just feel the dissonance between those two numbers — because that dissonance is the entire story.</p>
</section>

<section id="the-trial-data" class="reveal">
  <h2>What the Trials Actually Showed — and What They Were Actually Testing</h2>
  <p>The STEP-1 extension trial is worth revisiting carefully, because it is cited constantly and understood imprecisely. Published in <em>Diabetes, Obesity and Metabolism</em> in 2022, it followed participants who had completed 68 weeks of semaglutide 2.4 mg and then stopped. By week 120 — roughly one year post-discontinuation — they had regained a mean of 11.6 percentage points of body weight, representing approximately two-thirds of what they had lost. SURMOUNT-4, published in <em>JAMA</em> in 2024, told a similar story for tirzepatide: discontinuers regained an average of 14% of their body weight, roughly 11.1 kg, within 52 weeks — more than half of what the induction period had achieved.</p>
  <p>A January 2026 Oxford-led systematic review in the <em>BMJ</em>, analyzing 37 studies and more than 9,000 adults, found that weight regain after stopping GLP-1 drugs averages approximately 0.4 kg per month — four times faster than the regain observed after behavioral interventions alone. The modeled projection: return to baseline body weight within roughly 1.5 to 2 years for newer agents. A separate meta-analysis in <em>eClinicalMedicine</em> (The Lancet), covering 18 randomized controlled trials and 3,771 participants, found a mean weight regain of 5.63 kg in obesity patients after GLP-1 discontinuation, with semaglutide producing a larger rebound (8.21 kg) than liraglutide. The convergence across these analyses is real. The rebound is not a myth.</p>
  <p>But here is the methodological trap, and it is a significant one. In every one of these randomized controlled trials, participants who stopped the active drug were randomized to placebo. Not to a different obesity medication. Not to a dietitian. Not to a structured behavioral program. To a sugar injection and nothing else. The "rebound" these trials measure is not, strictly speaking, the pharmacological consequence of stopping a GLP-1 agonist. It is the consequence of stopping obesity treatment entirely — and then comparing that outcome to people who continued receiving it. That is a different question. And for years, the field has been answering the wrong one.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The 'rebound' that terrifies clinicians and patients is largely an artifact of comparing a treated population to an untreated one — not clean evidence that stopping GLP-1s is inherently catastrophic."</p></aside>

<section id="cleveland-clinic-data" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Cleveland Clinic Cohort: What Real-World Patients Actually Did</h2>
  <p>The Gasoyan study's headline number is striking, but the mechanism behind it is more important than the number itself. Among the 7,938 patients in the Cleveland Clinic cohort — drawn from a single large health system spanning Ohio and Florida — 19.6% restarted their original GLP-1 medication within a year of stopping. Another 35.2% received some form of alternative obesity treatment. In total, more than half of discontinuers continued treating their obesity in some way. Twenty-seven percent switched to a different medication. Fourteen percent engaged in lifestyle modification visits with dietitians or exercise specialists. Less than 1% underwent bariatric surgery.</p>
  <p>This is the variable that placebo-controlled trials, by design, cannot capture. Real-world patients stop a drug for a reason — cost, side effects, supply disruption — and then, frequently, do something else. Gasoyan's team found that the most common reasons for stopping were cost or insurance limitations and side effects, not lack of efficacy. These are patients who were still motivated. They didn't stop because the drug wasn't working. They stopped because the system made it difficult to continue.</p>
  <p>The diabetes subgroup result is even more striking. Patients treated for type 2 diabetes who stopped GLP-1 therapy actually lost an additional 1.3% of body weight in the year after discontinuation — a finding that likely reflects the relatively higher rate of alternative pharmacological management in that population, where metformin, SGLT-2 inhibitors, and other agents are routinely available and covered.</p>
  <p>The heterogeneity finding deserves its own sentence: 45% of obesity patients maintained or continued losing weight after stopping. Fifty-five percent gained. The average of 0.5% regain is real, but it is an average across a genuinely bimodal distribution. Nearly half the cohort did well. More than half did not. That split is clinically important, and the study does not yet tell us how to predict which group a given patient will fall into.</p>
  <p>Before this data is used to reassure anyone, its limitations must be named clearly. This is a retrospective, single-system, observational study. It relies on electronic health records and pharmacy dispensation data. It cannot establish causation. Patients who successfully transitioned to alternative treatments may be systematically different — better resourced, more engaged, more closely followed — from the broader population stopping GLP-1s. The study also only captured patients who stopped within 3 to 12 months of starting, potentially excluding longer-term users who may face different rebound dynamics after more extended pharmacological suppression. These are not footnote caveats. They are structural constraints on what the data can tell us.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Trial Data vs. Real-World Data: The Key Numbers</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>STEP-1 Extension (RCT, semaglutide):</strong> Two-thirds of lost weight regained within 1 year of stopping; mean 11.6 percentage points regained by week 120</li>
    <li><strong>SURMOUNT-4 (RCT, tirzepatide):</strong> ~14% body weight regained (~11.1 kg) within 52 weeks of stopping</li>
    <li><strong>BMJ Meta-Analysis (37 studies, 9,000+ adults):</strong> ~0.4 kg/month regain after stopping GLP-1s — 4× faster than after behavioral programs</li>
    <li><strong>eClinicalMedicine Meta-Analysis (18 RCTs, 3,771 participants):</strong> Mean regain of 5.63 kg; semaglutide 8.21 kg vs. liraglutide</li>
    <li><strong>Cleveland Clinic Cohort (7,938 real-world patients):</strong> Obesity patients regained average 0.5% body weight at 1 year; diabetes patients lost an additional 1.3%</li>
    <li><strong>Real-world treatment continuation:</strong> 19.6% restarted original GLP-1; 35.2% received alternative obesity treatment within 1 year of stopping</li>
    <li><strong>Outcome heterogeneity:</strong> 45% of obesity patients maintained or continued losing weight; 55% gained</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="the-biology" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Biology Doesn't Care About Your Insurance Coverage</h2>
  <p>The homeostatic counter-response to weight loss is one of the more elegant and infuriating features of human physiology. GLP-1 receptor agonists work by mimicking the endogenous gut hormone GLP-1, acting on receptors distributed across the pancreas, hypothalamus, brainstem, and vagus nerve. The pharmacological effect is multisystemic: appetite suppression, delayed gastric emptying, glucose-dependent insulin secretion, glucagon inhibition. The result is a sustained reduction in caloric intake that most people cannot achieve through willpower alone — not because they lack discipline, but because the neurohormonal architecture of hunger is genuinely powerful.</p>
  <p>When the drug stops, that architecture reasserts itself. Leptin levels fall as adipose tissue decreases, signaling the hypothalamus that energy stores are depleted. Ghrelin — the primary orexigenic hormone — rises. Resting metabolic rate decreases through metabolic adaptation, a phenomenon sometimes called hypometabolism, in which the body becomes more calorically efficient precisely when it can least afford to. Central anorexigenic signaling in the hypothalamus downregulates relatively quickly after GLP-1 receptor stimulation ends. Delayed gastric emptying reverses through restored antral motility. The net biological environment after stopping a potent GLP-1 agonist is one that strongly, actively promotes weight regain — and the greater the initial loss, the stronger the homeostatic counter-response. This is not a side effect of the drug. It is the body doing exactly what it evolved to do.</p>
  <p>Dr. Susan Wolver, writing from MedCentral, described the clinical reality plainly: "When patients voluntarily want to stop a GLP-1 RA, I taper doses rather than stopping abruptly. Even so, nearly all of these patients ultimately restart the medication due to increased hunger, food noise, and weight regain." Adam Collins, PhD, at the University of Surrey, has noted that weight regain is "amplified" when patients stop, particularly for those who relied on the drug without simultaneously building behavioral scaffolding. The biology is not softened by the real-world data. What the Cleveland Clinic study shows is that some patients successfully managed that biology through continued treatment. It does not show that the biology changed.</p>
  <p>The cardiometabolic dimension of this story is underreported and should not be. The <em>eClinicalMedicine</em> meta-analysis found that HbA1c, systolic blood pressure, waist circumference, and fasting plasma glucose all deteriorated significantly after GLP-1 discontinuation. The <em>BMJ</em> systematic review projected that cardiometabolic markers, like body weight, trend back toward baseline within 1.5 to 2 years of stopping. For a patient who started semaglutide because of elevated cardiovascular risk — which is most of them — this is not a cosmetic concern. The weight number on the scale is the visible proxy for a metabolic profile that is quietly worsening in ways that don't show up in a mirror.</p>
</section>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The biology is not softened by the real-world data. What the Cleveland Clinic study shows is that some patients successfully managed that biology through continued treatment. It does not show that the biology changed."</p></aside>

<section id="chronic-disease-framing" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Chronic-Disease Argument: Biologically Sound, Commercially Convenient</h2>
  <p>The dominant clinical framing of GLP-1 agonists — that they should be treated like antihypertensives, taken indefinitely because the underlying condition is chronic — is biologically defensible. Obesity is a chronic, relapsing condition with a strong neurohormonal basis. Stopping an antihypertensive causes blood pressure to rise. Stopping a GLP-1 agonist causes weight to rise. The analogy holds. Qi Sun, MD, at Harvard Medical School and Brigham and Women's Hospital, has argued in a <em>BMJ</em> editorial that GLP-1 receptor agonists should be used as adjuncts to, not replacements for, healthy dietary and lifestyle practices — a position that implicitly acknowledges the chronic-disease framing without fully endorsing indefinite pharmacotherapy for everyone.</p>
  <p>The tension worth naming is this: the argument for lifelong GLP-1 use is biologically sound and commercially optimal for manufacturers simultaneously. Novo Nordisk and Eli Lilly do not benefit from patients stopping. The chronic-disease framing, whatever its scientific merits, also happens to be the framing that maximizes prescription volume and revenue. That alignment does not make the science wrong. It does mean the framing deserves scrutiny that it has not always received, and that the voices most loudly advocating for indefinite treatment are not always the most disinterested ones in the room.</p>
  <p>Erica Spatz, MD, at Yale University School of Medicine, has raised a question that cuts through this tension productively: whether longer-term GLP-1 use could durably rewire the body's metabolic set point — not just suppress appetite pharmacologically, but actually alter the hormonal signaling environment such that patients are "reprogrammed" to maintain a lower body weight after stopping. "Is that sufficient to say that, hormonally, these incretin hormones have changed and that our brains are no longer getting those messages that we're hungry?" Spatz asked. "I think that's an open question." It is. And it is one of the most important questions in obesity medicine right now, because if the answer is yes — even for a subset of patients, even after a defined treatment duration — the entire calculus of lifelong therapy changes. We do not have that answer yet.</p>
</section>

<div class="info-card my-12 reveal">
  <h4 class="font-serif text-lg font-semibold mb-3 text-primary-700 dark:text-primary-400">Why Trial and Real-World Data Diverge: The Methodological Gap</h4>
  <ul class="space-y-2 text-sm">
    <li><strong>RCT placebo arms:</strong> Participants who stop active drug receive no alternative treatment — measuring the effect of stopping all obesity treatment, not just the drug</li>
    <li><strong>Real-world discontinuers:</strong> 54.8% received some form of continued obesity treatment within 1 year (19.6% restarted original GLP-1; 35.2% received alternatives)</li>
    <li><strong>Reason for stopping matters:</strong> Most real-world patients stopped due to cost or side effects — not lack of efficacy — meaning motivation to treat obesity remained intact</li>
    <li><strong>What the gap does NOT mean:</strong> That stopping GLP-1s is biologically safe — the homeostatic counter-response (leptin fall, ghrelin rise, metabolic adaptation) is identical regardless of insurance coverage</li>
    <li><strong>What the gap DOES mean:</strong> That treatment continuity — in any form — substantially modifies post-discontinuation outcomes, and that the trial data measures a scenario most real-world patients don't face</li>
  </ul>
</div>

<section id="the-real-story" class="reveal">
  <h2>The Real Story Is Structural, Not Pharmacological</h2>
  <p>About half of all people with obesity stop using GLP-1 drugs within a year of starting. That is not a fringe phenomenon. A large JAMA Network Open cohort of 125,474 patients found that 46.5% of those with type 2 diabetes and 64.8% of those without discontinued within one year. Real-world discontinuation rates range from 37% to 81% depending on the population and data source. The post-discontinuation question is not a niche clinical concern. It is the central clinical reality of GLP-1 prescribing.</p>
  <p>The Cleveland Clinic data offers a genuinely encouraging finding: many patients who stop do not simply fall off a cliff. They transition. They restart. They find alternatives. The treatment journey continues even when the specific prescription does not. Gasoyan put it plainly: "Many patients do not give up on their obesity treatment journey, even if they need to stop their initial medication." That is real, and it matters.</p>
  <p>But the same JAMA Network Open study that documented discontinuation rates also found that lower income was significantly associated with higher discontinuation rates among diabetes patients. This is the closing image that the rest of the data cannot soften. The patients most likely to stop GLP-1 therapy are the patients least likely to have the treatment alternatives — the follow-on prescriptions, the dietitian visits, the structured behavioral programs — that explain the muted rebound in the Cleveland Clinic cohort. The 45% of obesity patients who maintained or continued losing weight after stopping were, in all probability, not uniformly distributed across the income spectrum. The patients cycling through cost-driven discontinuation without a safety net to catch them are not well-represented in a single large health system's electronic health records.</p>

<aside class="pull-quote reveal"><p>"The biology is the same for everyone. The safety net is not."</p></aside>

  <p>The real-world data does not tell us stopping is safe. It tells us that what happens after stopping matters enormously — and that our healthcare system's ability to provide that continuity is uneven, expensive, and heavily correlated with income. The homeostatic counter-response does not check your insurance status before activating. Leptin falls the same way in a patient who has a follow-up appointment with an obesity medicine specialist and in a patient who has nothing. The biology is the same for everyone. The safety net is not. That gap — not the one between trial data and real-world data, but the one between patients who can afford continuity and those who cannot — is the story that the next decade of GLP-1 research needs to take seriously.</p>
</section>

